var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"location":"#AnotherParser","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser","text":"Documentation for AnotherParser.\n\nAnotherParser allows one to implement a recursive descent parser given a hierarchical grammar expressed as BNF.\n\nNeither ISO EBNF nor W3C EBNF are currently supported.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Grammars","page":"Home","title":"Grammars","text":"A grammar is represented by a BNFGrammar struct. AllGrammars is a catalog of all of the defined grammars.\n\nEach BNFGrammar includes a collection of [DerivationRule]@ref)s. Each DerivationRule has a \"left hand side' that is a tree of BNFNodes.\n\nA DerivationRule can be referred to by name via BNFRef, and thus shared among different parts of the grammar and between grammars.\n\nEach BNFNode implements the recognize generic function, which performs the actual parsing:","category":"section"},{"location":"#Utility-Functions","page":"Home","title":"Utility Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Construction-Utilities","page":"Home","title":"Construction Utilities","text":"A grammar has little use recognizing its input if it does not also build a useful data structure from the abstract syntax tree.\n\nAll BNFNode types should describe what their recognize methods return as a value.  For CharacterLiteral and StringLiteral it is just the matched character or string.  For RegexNode it is the regular expression's match object.  For Alternatives it is the value of whatever subexpression matched.  For Sequence it is a Vector of the matched values of the subexpressions.\n\nThe Constructor BNFNode type can be used to wrap another BNFNode expression to massage the value that it returns.\n\nAlso, DerivationRule can be assigned a constructor property.\n\nVarious functions are provided to serve as constructors.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Constructor-Functions","page":"Home","title":"Constructor Functions","text":"The application usually wants to construct some form of data structure during the parsing operation, not just a simple tree representing the result of the parse.  Both Constructor and DerivationRule allow for a constructor function to be called on the currently recognized input and return instead an object that is meaningful to the application.  Each constructor function takes as arguments:\n\na context object that is meaningless to everything but the constructor function;\nthe entire input string;\nthe start index into that input string of the portion currently recognized;\nthe index of the last character to have been matched (so that a constructtor could just call SubString);\nthe subordinate fragments (values) that were just parsed.\n\nFor convenience, some constructor functions are already provided:","category":"section"},{"location":"#Example","page":"Home","title":"Example","text":"using AnotherParser\n\n# A grammar is named by a symbol\nBNFGrammar(:example)\n\n# \"text\" can be one word, or a sequence of words separated by spaces:\n# Note the two uses of Constructor so that the result will be a\n# single, flat Tuple of words:\nDerivationRule(\n    :example,\n    \"text\",\n    Alternatives(\n        Constructor(BNFRef(:example, \"word\"),\n                    (context, input::AbstractString, from::Int, to::Int, x) -> (x,)),\n        Constructor(\n            Sequence(BNFRef(:example, \"word\"),\n                     BNFRef(:example, \"space\"),\n                     BNFRef(:example, \"text\")),\n            (context, input::AbstractString, from::Int, to::Int, x) -> (x[1], x[3]...))))\n\n# Collapse the successive characters of a word into a string:\nDerivationRule(\n    :example,\n    \"word\",\n    BNFRef(:example, \"word1\")).constructor = substring_constructor_function\n\n# \"word1\" is a sequence of letters:\nDerivationRule(\n    :example,\n    \"word1\",\n    Alternatives(BNFRef(:example, \"letter\"),\n                 Sequence(BNFRef(:example, \"letter\"),\n                          BNFRef(:example, \"word1\"))))\n\n# Lowercase letters\nDerivationRule(\n    :example,\n    \"letter\",\n    Alternatives([CharacterLiteral(c) for c in 'a':'z']...))\n\n# Whitespace:\nDerivationRule(\n    :example,\n    \"space\",\n    Alternatives(\n        CharacterLiteral(' '),\n        Sequence(\n            CharacterLiteral(' '),\n            BNFRef(:example, \"space\"))))\n\n# recognize will return a tuple of \"word\"s and\n# the next index of the input string\nrecognize(AllGrammars[:example][\"text\"],\n          \"this  is    a test\")\n\nThere is much room for simplification and syntactic sugar.\n\nAdditional examples are available in the ./examples directory.  This includes a grammar for parsing SemVer semantic version number format, a grammar for BNF as specified on the Wikipedia BNF page, and the full W3C XML grammar.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Debugging","page":"Home","title":"Debugging","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#The-Grammar-for-BNF","page":"Home","title":"The Grammar for BNF","text":"The grammar for BNF itself is specified as BNF.  The file ./examples/BNF/bnf.jl implements two BNF grammars. :BootstrapBNFGrammar is a grammar that is hand coded using BNFNode types.  :BNF is automatically built by the :BootstrapBNFGrammar grammar.\n\nThere is some machinery to orchestrate that.  I won't decribe it here. I hope the implementation is clear enough.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Index","page":"Home","title":"Index","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.BNFGrammar","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.BNFGrammar","text":"BNFGrammar\n\nRepresents a single grammar which can consist of a number of DerivationRules.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.AllGrammars","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.AllGrammars","text":"A Dict of all defined grammars.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"constant"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.Alternatives","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.Alternatives","text":"Alternatives(nodes...)\n\nMatches any one element of nodes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.BNFNode","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.BNFNode","text":"BNFNode\n\nAbstract supertype for all structs that we use to implement a grammar.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.BNFRef","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.BNFRef","text":"BNFRef(grammar, name)\n\ndelegates to the \"left hand side\" of the DerivationRule named name in grammar.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.CharacterInSet","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.CharacterInSet","text":"CharacterInSet(set)\n\nMatches any single character in set.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.CharacterLiteral","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.CharacterLiteral","text":"CharacterLiteral(c)\n\nMatches the single character c.\n\nFor efficiency ans simplicity, consider using CharacterInSet or CharacterSatisfiesPredicate instead of Alternatives(CharacterLiteral(...), CharacterLiteral(...), ...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.CharacterSatisfiesPredicate","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.CharacterSatisfiesPredicate","text":"CharacterSatisfiesPredicate(predicate::Function)\n\nMatches any single character that predicate returns true for.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.Constructor","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.Constructor","text":"Constructor(node, constructor_function)\n\nApply constructor_function to the result of recognizing node and return that as the result.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.DerivationRule","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.DerivationRule","text":"DerivationRule(grammar, rule_name, expression)\n\nImplements a single production named name in the specified grammar. One can include expression in other expressions using BNFRef(grammar, rule_name). The rule can have a constructor function, which, if present, will be called with the recognized value, and the context.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.Empty","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.Empty","text":"Empty()\n\nSucceed while matching nothing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.EndOfInput","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.EndOfInput","text":"EndOfInput()\n\nSucceed if input is exhausted.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.Excluding","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.Excluding","text":"Excluding(exclude, match)\n\nMatch if the current input matches match, but ofly if it does not match exclude.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.RegexNode","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.RegexNode","text":"RegexNode <: BNFNode(re::Regex)\n\nMatch the specified regular expression. So that the parser can access captures, The second return value of recognize is the RegexMatch object returned by match.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.Repeat","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.Repeat","text":"Repeat(n::BNFNode; min=0, max=typemax(Int))\n\nMatches repeated occurances of n.  The minimum and maxmum number of allowed matches can be specified.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.Sequence","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.Sequence","text":"Sequence(nodes...)\n\nSuccessively match each of nodes in turn.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.StringLiteral","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.StringLiteral","text":"StringLiteral(str)\n\nMatches the string str.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.recognize","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.recognize","text":"recognize(::Parser, ::BNFNode, input::AbstractString; index, finish, context)\n\nAttempt to parse input as the specified BNFNode, starting at index. Return three values: whether the node matched the input, the parsed value represented by the matched input, and the next index into input. finish is the index into input of the last character to be considered. The context argument is passed to constructor functions (see Constructor and DerivationRule) but is otherwise unused.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.show_grammar","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.show_grammar","text":"show_grammar(grammar_name::Symbol)\n\nShow a pretty description of all of the derivations in the grammar.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.check_references","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.check_references","text":"check_references(grammar)::Bool\n\nWarn of any BNFRef nodes in the grammar that don't have a target. Return true if there are any issues.\n\nReturns true if any warnings were issued.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.pretty","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.pretty","text":"pretty(::BNFNode)\n\nReturn a human-readable string that describes the node.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.is_left_recursive","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.is_left_recursive","text":"is_left_recursive(::BNFGrammar)\nis_left_recursive(::DerivationRule)\nis_left_recursive(node::BNFNode, grammar::Symbol, name::AbstractString)\n\nReturns true is node is left recursive with respect to the DerivationRule named name.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.walk_nodes","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.walk_nodes","text":"walk_nodes(f, node)\n\nApplies f to each node in the node tree that descends from node.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.deep_flatten","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.deep_flatten","text":"deep_flatten(collection)\n\nFlattens an arbitrarily deeply nested collection.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.identity_constructor_function","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.identity_constructor_function","text":"identity_constructor_function(context, input::AbstractString, from::Int, to::Int, value)\n\nA constructor function that just returns the raw value from its associated DerivationRule or subexpression.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.substring_constructor_function","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.substring_constructor_function","text":"substring_constructor_function(context, input::AbstractString, from::Int, to::Int, value)\n\nA constructor function that ruturns the matched substring.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.value_is_from_index","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.value_is_from_index","text":"value_is_from_index(context, input::AbstractString, from::Int, to::Int, value)\n\nUses the from index as the constructor value for the associated node.  This is useful if some higher BNFNode will be using SubString to construct its value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.value_is_to_index","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.value_is_to_index","text":"value_is_to_index(context, input::AbstractString, from::Int, to::Int, value) = to\n\nUses the to index as the constructor value for the associated node. This is useful if some higher BNFNode will be using SubString to construct its value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.value_is","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.value_is","text":"value_is(value)\n\nReturns a constructor function that always returns value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.flattening_constructor_function","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.flattening_constructor_function","text":"flattening_constructor_function(context, input::AbstractString, from::Int, to::Int, value)\n\nReturns a flattened list given an arbitrarily nested one.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.debug_parsing","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.debug_parsing","text":"debug_parsing(grammar::BNFGrammar, rulename::AbstractString, input::AbstractString; index = 1, finish = length(input), context=nothing, report_file::AbstractString, enable_debug_logging_for = should_enable_debug_logging_for)\n\nRun the parser specified by grammar and rulename to parse input from index to finish with the specified context object.  The parsing log is written to report_file as HTML.  That file presents a hierarchichal view of how the parse progressed.\n\nenabledebuglogging_for is a function that takes a BNFNode as argument and returns true if that node should be tracked in the info log and false otherwise.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.DEBUG_BNFNODES","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.DEBUG_BNFNODES","text":"DEBUG_BNFNODES\n\nDEBUG_BNFNODES is a list of the node uid's of nodes that should be @info logged when they match the current input at the specified index.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"constant"},{"location":"#AnotherParser.should_enable_debug_logging_for","page":"Home","title":"AnotherParser.should_enable_debug_logging_for","text":"should_enable_debug_logging_for(node::BNFNode)\n\nThe default value for the enable_debug_logging_for keyword argument to debug_parsing.\n\nIt avoids logging of CharacterLiteral nodes and of Alternatives nodes where every alternative is a `CharacterLiteral node.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"}]
}
